October 28,1956 was the date of Elvis's second &quot;historic&quot; appearance on The Ed Sullivan Show. When they arrived in New York, Elvis and his friends checked into the posh Warwick Hotel located at 54th Street and Sixth Avenue.Elvis was chauffered by limo to the Sullivan Theatre on Broadway where a large throng of girls was waiting for him at the back entrance. As he was being escorted towards the theatre door, Elvis heard the voice of an elderly woman calling his name. She was waving one of his record albums in the air and asking him to autograph it. A studio executive attempted to force Elvis inside, but he pushed the man back. The executive shouted, &quot;Come on, you don't have time for autographs now! Fifty million people are waiting to see you.&quot; Elvis ignored him and went over to autograph the album for the woman. He turned to the executive and said, &quot;Listen, if she can take the time to buy my album, then by God, I can spare the time to sign it.&quot; He then stormed inside and got ready to go onstage.
The crowd cheered long and loud in support of Elvis's loyalty. They made so much noise that a security guard had to come out and hush them. The audience inside could not hear above the racket.

