In March and April 1964, Elvis was filming a fight scene for &quot;Roustabout&quot; in which he was to knock down stunt man Glenn Wilder with a karate chop. As Wilder fell to the ground, his leg flew out and made contact with Elvis's head.Blood spurted out of the wound and everyone on the set panicked. Several crew members inspected the wound and decided it was just a scratch. The studio nurse tried for over an hour to stop the bleeding but it would not subside. When the doctor was called he diagnosed the &quot;scratch&quot; as a two inch laceration which could only be closed with stitches.
Elvis was taken to Conejo Medical Square inThousand Oaks, where Dr. Daniel MacGillis closed his wound with nine stitches. he prescribed pain medication and antibiotics to prevent infection. As Elvis was ordered to wear bandages for two weeks, his wound was incorporated into the movie. Until the day he died, Elvis sported a small scar above his left eyebrow.

