Actor Lorne Greene, star of the famous TV Western series, Bonanza, was the honorary chairman of the Dunaoff School for Mentally Retarded Children. In 1965, Elvis heard about the charity and wanted to contribute something that would help the children. He decided to donate his 1962 Dodge motorhome to the school. When Greene heard about Elvis's donation, he met with the singer and accepted the gift on the school's behalf. The two talked for several hours. Elvis complimented Greene's work, explaining that he was an avid western fan and that one of his favorites was Bonanza. Greene was delighted that Elvis knew so much about him and was thrilled to personally accept his donation.
The motor home was eventually auctioned off and the sizeable proceeds went to the school. Lorne thanked Elvis and told him that his donation was benefiting a great cause. Because of his generosity, doctors would be able to buy better equipment and the children would be more comfortable. Elvis thanked Greene and graciously answered that it was worth the time and effort if it meant he could help needy children.

